analysis: The documents all relate to the designation of various international organizations as public international organizations, granting them certain privileges, exemptions, and immunities under the International Organizations Immunities Act. The documents specify the legal basis for the designation, often referencing treaties, acts of Congress, or other international agreements that authorize U.S. participation in these organizations. The documents also include language clarifying that the designation is not intended to diminish any existing privileges or immunities the organizations may already possess.
title: International Organizations Immunities Designations
